title: Brisbane Ranges National Park - Plants
description:
A collection of vascular plants found within the Brisbane Ranges National Park and adjoining Steiglitz Historic Park. Any observations found within the boundaries of the reserve can be included.
For observations on adjoining private land within the broader Brisbane Ranges landscape, there is another collection called "Brisbane Ranges surrounds - Plants".
If you find a species in the national park or historic reserve that is not currently part of this collection, please notify me for inclusion - chris.lindorff@bigpond.com. Thanks.

items.title: Melianthus comosus
items.content_text: Very hardy weed that has colonised along the edges of the Sutherland's Creek south of Steiglitz. Infestations of multiple patches along creek, from 5 to 100s of plants. Photos taken by Jo Day.

items.title: Pterostylis aciculiformis
items.content_text: Although this plant is just outside the boundaries of the National Park, they are also found within the park.  This plant appeared spontaneously this year - I have not seen it before in this location. Note the second photo for close-up of the labellum.

items.title: Caladenia fuscata
items.content_text: White coloured C fuscata (Dusky Fingers). ID'd on the basis of features such as the forward-pointing triangular extensions on mid-lobes, lack of yellow on lip/tip of labellum, glands on back of dorsal sepal and underneath sepals and petals. However noted a lack of prominent red transverse stripes on and underneath the labellum. Other C. fuscata nearby displayed the stripes extending further up the lobes and underneath the labellum. Just a variation perhaps in this plant? 4 pics.

items.title: Corunastylis archeri
items.content_text: Flowering time Nov - March.  Grows in many habitats.  Flower dorsal sepal and petals lack hairs, labellum is fringed with medium to longish hairs.

items.title: Caladenia transitoria
items.content_text: Flowering period Oct - Nov.  Plant usually about 100mm tall and difficult to see in habitat.  Labellum has dark purple calli and petals usually yellowish-green.

items.title: Caladenia cucullata
items.content_text: Flowers are white, labellum has red to purple calli.  Common in inland areas.

items.title: Grevillea micrantha
items.content_text: The Brisbane Ranges form has leaves with granules confined to the veins on upper surface and broader grooves on undersurface.  Found mainly in western and central Victoria.  The climate is hot dry summers, cold wet winters, rainfall around 500mm annually.

items.title: Grevillea micrantha
items.content_text: Commonly known as Small-leaf Grevillea.  The flowers are white to pale pink and often hidden in the dull green foliage.

items.title: Grevillea steiglitziana
items.content_text: This grevillea is a low spreading shrub with shiny, lightly toothed, holly-like leaves and bright red toothbrush flowers.  It is found in Victoria, mostly confined to the Brisbane Ranges between Geelong & Bacchus marsh.  Grows in dry, open eucalypt forest

items.title: Xanthorrhoea australis
items.content_text:
The stalk of this Grass Tree (Xanthorrhoea spp.)seems to be suffering from vertigo?

These were all burnt in bush fires last year (2005), which causes them to flower.

Brisbane Ranges National Park, near Anakie, Victoria.

items.title: Pterostylis smaragdyna
items.content_text:
Flowers in Winter (Jun - Aug), favours low flats, well drained - loamy soil in open forest.
Labellum contains small bristles and retracts when disturbed.  Lateral sepals touching at base of flower.
